Wreck Site Map From 2010 Expedition
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/titanic-map.jpg
                    
					A collaboration between various partners, the 2010 expedition to the Titanic wreck site produced the first comprehensive map of the 15-square-mile debris field. AUVs (autonomous underwater vehicles) and an ROV (remote operated vehicle) were used in conjunction to harness cutting-edge 2-D, 3-D and sonar technology.
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Titanic’s Bow
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/titanic-bow.jpg
                    
					When Titanic sank in the early hours of April 15, 1912, its stern and bow sections separated. The two pieces came to rest roughly 2,000 feet apart from one another on the ocean floor, 2.3 miles below the surface of the North Atlantic.
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					The Deckhouse Debris
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/deckhouse-debris.jpg
                    
					The so-called deckhouse debris, a pile of rubble located at a significant distance from the rest of the wreckage, was of particular interest to the HISTORY analysts during the 2010 expedition. Containing the base of Titanic’s third funnel and surrounding decks, this piece and its location in relation to other elements helped experts reconstruct how the ship broke apart.
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Pieces of Titanic’s Double Bottom
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/double-bottom.jpg
                    
					Once a single piece encasing the hull, Titanic’s double bottom is thought to have split apart after the ship broke in half. It has otherwise remained relatively intact over the last century.
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Titanic’s Stern and Surrounding Debris
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/titanic-stern.jpg
                    
					A cloud of debris lies beside Titanic’s stern, containing remnants of the galley and upper decks, three baggage cranes, boilers and cylinders, among numerous other pieces. This zone is considered “ground zero” of the sinking, which is thought to have occurred directly above the area.
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					The “Bigger Piece”
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/bigger-piece.jpg
                    
					Salvaged in 1998, the 15-ton “Big Piece” is featured in Titanic: The Artifact Exhibition in Las Vegas. HISTORY analysts dubbed a larger chunk of wreckage encompassing several decks the “Bigger Piece” for this reason.
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Cover of Titanic’s Number-One Cargo Hatch
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/cargo-hatch.jpg
                    
					Located at the far edge of the debris field beyond the bow, the cover of Titanic’s number-one cargo hatch is thought to have blown off the ship when water burst out of the bow as it slammed into the ocean floor.
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Funnel Remains
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/funnel-remains.jpg
                    
					The remains of one of Titanic’s funnels have been positively identified, buried in the sand with only the black band around its top having survived. An entire set of whistles is still attached to it.
																                        				  la                                
                        															
						
				
			
            	
			
			
							
					
					
				
					            
					
				
				
					
				
				
				
				
		
	
